1-3 Sutton Place (originally called Ave., A), at and adjoining the N.E. corner of 57th Street. About 1922.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

Sutton Place (originally called Ave. A), south from 58th Street (Sutton Square), to and including 57th Street.

1925.

Brown Brothers.

Sutton Place (originally called Ave. A), at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of 57th Street. Also shown is 57th Street, north side, east from Sutton Place (Ave. A), to the East River.

September 20, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

Sutton Place (originally called Ave., A), north from but not including 57th Street. The Queensboro Bridge is seen in the background running east on 59th Street, over the East River to Long Island City.

September 20, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

East 57th Street, west from and including Sutton Place. Note the Ritz Tower in the background.

1928.

New York Edison Company.

57th Street, west from and including Sutton Place. In the distance is the Ritz Tower.
1931.
Wurts Brothers.

Sutton Place (originally called Ave. A), at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of 57th Street.
January 14, 1931.

International News Photos.

Sutton Place (originally called Ave. A), north from and including 57th Street. The Queensboro Bridge is seen in the background, which extends from Second Ave., and 59th Street, Manhattan, to Bridge Plaza, in the Borough of Queens, along East 59th Street.

January 14, 1932.

International News Photos.

(1)

Sutton Place (originally called Avenue A), west side, south from but not including 59th, to and including 57th Streets, as seen from the Queensboro Bridge.

March 5, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

The same, from a different angle.

(1)
East River, south from East 57th Street, showing the 13-story apartment house No. 1 Sutton Place South; the brewery of the Consumers Brewing Co.; and the River House (center). Also shown is the skyline of Mid-town Manhattan with the Chrysler and Empire State Buildings visible in the center background. The point of vantage is the Queensborough Bridge.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, another view from the same vantage point. The Chrysler Building, here, obstructs the view of the Empire State.
March 5, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
The same, at a later date. The vantage point is Welfare Island.
May 4, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
title: East River - Shore and skyline of Manhattan from East 57th Street - [Sutton Place ] - Williamsburg and Queensborough Bridges.

"Changing New York"
Photographs by Berenice Abbott

Title: Sutton Place: Anne Morgan's Town House Place: Northeast corner of East 57th Street, Manhattan
Date: April 2, 1936

7 Sutton Place, east side, north of E. 57th Street, showing the entrance to the Marshall Kernochan home. Miss Anne Morgan home is on the right. This was leased to Frank M. Gould according to the N. Y. Times of October 6, 1937.

1938-9

Alexander Alland

This photo is one of a series that appeared in the published volume "Portrait of N. Y." by Felix Reisenberg and Alex. Alland, IRGV.

title: Sutton Place - 57th Street east side - looking north
